Operating in wavelet space provides two advantages: (i) explicit separation of global brightness (LL) from high-frequency boundaries, (ii) structured control over target–background detail without full 3D pixel-space diffusion.
3.2.5 Wavelet-Aware Training Objective
Unlike standard diffusion trained with uniform loss, SALIENT optimizes a frequency-structured objective that disentangles global structure from boundary detail.
We define a band-weighted reconstruction:
where applies higher weights near lesion boundaries and moderates diagonal HH amplification.
To stabilize brightness and prevent drift in low-prevalence regimes, we introduce low-frequency moment regularization:
High-frequency variance control ensures texture fidelity without noise amplification:
Finally, mild pixel-space auxiliary constraints encourage edge alignment and prevent intensity saturation in lesion and peri-lesional regions.
